<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06042n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06042n">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06042n"> 42(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> triumph of <font color="green">[sons]</font> / strike earth</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Voici des petits gar&ccedil;ons qui se battaient pour jouer: ils poursuivaient un but, la victoire sur l&apos;adversaire. Mais supposons qu&apos;ils luttent maintenant devant des spectateurs et qu&apos;ils ont tout arrang&eacute; d&apos;avance: je te donnerai &agrave; ce moment l&apos;occasion de me saisir, <mark>tu me jetteras par terre</mark>, mais j&apos;ex&eacute;cuterai tout &agrave; coup un mouvement qui m&apos;assurera la victoire &hellip; Si, dans ce cas, il n&apos;est plus question pour les enfants <mark>de triompher de l&apos;adversaire</mark>, ils n&apos;en poursuivent pas moins un autre but, &agrave; savoir: agir sur les spectateurs. <font color="green">[Here are little boys who were fighting to play: they pursued a goal, the victory over the opponent. But suppose that they are now fighting in front of the spectators and that they have arranged everything in advance: I will give you the opportunity at this moment to seize me, you will throw me on the ground, but I will suddenly execute a movement which will assure me of the victory ... If, in this case, it is no longer a question for the children to triumph over the opponent, they still pursue another goal, namely: to act on the spectators.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 57-8</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
